HashSet is overkill for this.  Just use a boolean [] since the index is known. E.g for i+j,  rightToLeft[i+j] = true. For the negative, an array still works with a fixed offset of 9, leftToRight[9+i-j] = true.  No more HashSet, or method calls in the main loop.

As for the algorithm in general, you could use recursion.  You&#39;ve got to consider, what if I don&#39;t place the first bishop at 0,0?  Basically, once you&#39;ve found one solution you need to back out your last placement and check if a bishop would have also fit at the position after that (and repeat).  Once you&#39;ve exhausted all possibilities for the last position, then back up and try different possibilities for the second last position, etc.  Remember the board state for the maximum bishops placed and discard any board states that have less than your current maximum.

```
public class MaxBishop {
    private static final int DIM = 10;
    private static final int DIM_M_1 = DIM-1;
    private static final int DIM_SQ = DIM*DIM;
    static boolean[] leftToRight = new boolean[2*DIM];
    static boolean[] rightToLeft = new boolean[2*DIM];

    static boolean[] matrix = new boolean[DIM_SQ];

    static int maxBishops = 0;

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        maxBishop(0,0);
    }

    public static void maxBishop(int start, int numPlaced) {
        for (int p = start; p &lt; DIM_SQ; p++) {
            int i = p / DIM;
